<Findings version="1" source="LLR" source_version="1">
  <Finding ID="LLR--1--1">
    <ItemID>HL-*</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      Multiple High-Level Requirements contain relationship tags &lt;Dependency&gt; instead of the specified &lt;DependsOn&gt; tag, violating the SRP structure definition (1.1.3, 2.1.1) and making traceability inconsistent between HLR and LLR.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      In all High-Level Requirements, replace each &lt;Dependency&gt; tag with &lt;DependsOn&gt;. For example, for HL-RUN-1.3 use:
      &lt;Relationships&gt;
        &lt;DependsOn&gt;HL-PLAN-1.1&lt;/DependsOn&gt;
      &lt;/Relationships&gt;
      and apply the same pattern consistently for HL-INTERF-2.2, HL-INTERF-2.3, HL-INTERF-3.2, HL-INTERF-3.3, HL-INTERF-3.4, HL-HARDWARE-2.2, HL-HARDWARE-2.3, HL-ENV-1.2, HL-ENV-1.3, HL-ENV-1.4, HL-ENV-2.1, HL-ENV-3.1.
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--2">
    <ItemID>HL-MAP-1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      The High-Level requirement HL-MAP-1.1 “Explore Maze” is only partially refined by the existing LLRs. The HLR states: “The system shall autonomously explore an unknown maze.” but the LLR set does not fully cover:
      - how the exploration is commanded from the main control perspective (interface/protocol with the main control module),
      - how exploration behavior is coordinated with other system modes (e.g., idle, return, second run),
      - handling of unreachable regions or exploration failure conditions beyond the time budget.
      This violates SRP 2.1.1 (4) and (5): every part of the HLR must be refined and all LLR content must trace to HLRs in a complete manner suitable for architecture derivation.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Refine HL-MAP-1.1 with additional LLRs to cover the missing aspects. For example:
      - Add an LLR defining the main control module interface for starting/stopping exploration (e.g., “The system shall expose a function exploration_start() and exploration_stop() callable by the main control module, and shall ignore further exploration_start() commands while exploration is active.”).
      - Add an LLR specifying exploration mode/state management and interaction with run/second-run logic (e.g., “The system shall maintain a navigation state machine with at least the states IDLE, EXPLORATION, RETURN, SECOND_RUN and shall only accept exploration commands in the IDLE state.”).
      - Add an LLR defining handling of unreachable frontier cells or failure modes (e.g., “The system shall signal an exploration failure result to the main control module when exploration terminates with remaining unreachable unknown cells.”).
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--3">
    <ItemID>HL-RUN-1.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-RUN-1.3 “Efficient Path Execution” content states: “The Second run shall follow the fastest path to the target” but:
      - Its relationship uses an incorrect &lt;Dependency&gt; tag and references “HL--PLAN--3.1” which does not exist and violates the ID pattern.
      - The LLRs LL-RUN-1.3.1 and LL-RUN-1.3.2 refine aspects of “fastest path” and high-speed execution, but there is no correct HLR-level dependency on the actual planning HLR (HL-PLAN-1.1) in HL-RUN-1.3.
      This breaks traceability (SRP 2.1.2 (2)) and undermines deriving a consistent architecture.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      - Fix HL-RUN-1.3 relationships to:
        &lt;Relationships&gt;
          &lt;DependsOn&gt;HL-PLAN-1.1&lt;/DependsOn&gt;
        &lt;/Relationships&gt;
      - Verify that all LLRs refining HL-RUN-1.3 are consistent with this corrected dependency.
      - Remove any reference to the non-existent “HL--PLAN--3.1” ID.
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--4">
    <ItemID>HL-INTERF-2.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-INTERF-2.3 content: “The system shall account for an approximate front ultrasonic sensor accuracy of �2 cm” contains an invalid character sequence “�2 cm” instead of a clear accuracy specification. This makes the requirement ambiguous and not testable, violating SRP 3.4 (3) and 3.1.1 (3).
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Correct the wording to a clear and unambiguous form, e.g.:
      “The system shall account for an approximate front ultrasonic sensor accuracy of ±2 cm.”
      Ensure the encoding in the requirements document correctly represents the ± symbol or replace it by plain text “plus or minus 2 cm”.
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--5">
    <ItemID>HL-INTERF-3.4</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-INTERF-3.4 content: “... mounted at approximately 25� angles ...” includes an invalid “�” character instead of a proper degree indicator. This is ambiguous and can lead to misinterpretation of the sensor orientation, which several LLRs (e.g., LL-MAP-1.2.3, LL-INTERF-1.1.2) rely on for architecture and algorithm design.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      Replace “25�” with a clear form, e.g. “25 degrees” or “25°”, ensuring proper encoding. For example:
      “The system shall expect data from infrared sensors mounted at approximately 25 degrees relative to the robot front direction.”
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--6">
    <ItemID>HL-HARDWARE-2.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-HARDWARE-2.2 (Rotational Velocity) expresses: “The system shall not assume a constant rotational speed” and is tagged as NFR, but:
      - Its relationships use &lt;Dependency&gt; rather than &lt;DependsOn&gt;.
      - LLR LL-HARDWARE-2.2.1 (“Rotational Speed Independence”) refines HL-HARDWARE-2.2 and is NFR, but this HLR is also referenced indirectly by LL-HARDWARE-2.1.2 (odometry-free estimation) which may implicitly rely on specific rotational behavior.
      The incorrect relationship tagging and missing explicit HLR–LLR linkage for all impacts makes the design constraints hard to trace and can misguide architecture (controllers and motion estimation strategies).
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      - Fix HL-HARDWARE-2.2 relationships to use &lt;DependsOn&gt; only if actually needed, or remove the dependency if unnecessary.
      - Explicitly verify and, if needed, add missing &lt;Refines&gt; relations at LLR level where HL-HARDWARE-2.2 constraints are applied (e.g., LL-HARDWARE-2.1.2 already refines it; confirm this is complete).
      - Revalidate that controller and estimation-related LLRs are consistent with “no constant rotational speed” assumption.
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--7">
    <ItemID>HL-HARDWARE-2.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-HARDWARE-2.3 says: “... handle speeds from 0cm/s ... up to 200cm/s ... but limit the actual high speed in order to avoid collisions.” Several LLRs refine parts of this (LL-HARDWARE-2.3.1, LL-MAP-1.2.4, LL-RUN-1.3.2, LL-PLAN-1.1.2), but the HLR itself:
      - Uses &lt;Dependency&gt; instead of &lt;DependsOn&gt;,
      - Does not clearly separate environmental capability (speed handling range) from design constraints (limiting speed for safety),
      - Leaves open whether 200 cm/s is a hard bound, nominal bound, or design-time configurable maximum.
      This makes complete and consistent refinement difficult and impairs architecture decisions about speed control modules.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      - Replace &lt;Dependency&gt; with &lt;DependsOn&gt; in HL-HARDWARE-2.3.
      - Clarify HL-HARDWARE-2.3 into separate, unambiguous statements if necessary, for example:
        1) “The system shall support commanded translational speeds between 0 cm/s and 200 cm/s.”
        2) “The system shall enforce a configurable maximum operational speed not exceeding 200 cm/s to limit collision risk.”
      - Then verify and, if needed, adjust LLRs (LL-HARDWARE-2.3.1, LL-MAP-1.2.4, LL-RUN-1.3.2, LL-PLAN-1.1.2) to refine these clarified statements precisely.
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--8">
    <ItemID>HL-PLAN-1.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-PLAN-1.1: “The system shall compute an optimal path to the target” is broad. The LLR set covers graph construction, cost definition, algorithm selection, goal region planning, and path representation. However, the HLR does not define:
      - What constitutes a “target” in the context of return runs vs second runs vs general objectives,
      - Whether “optimal” is in terms of distance, time, or another metric (this is pushed down to LL-PLAN-1.1.2),
      - The interface and responsibilities for specifying start/target cells and receiving paths.
      This can cause architectural ambiguity about which module owns path requests and life-cycle, and strictly speaking means not every part of the HLR is clearly traceable as required by SRP 2.1.1 (4).
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      - Refine HL-PLAN-1.1 text to explicitly define:
        - The optimization criterion (e.g., minimal traversal time or distance),
        - That “target” includes both goal region cells and start cell (for return),
        - The role of the planning subsystem as a service with a clearly defined interface.
      - Optionally add an additional HLR (e.g., “Planning Service Interface”) that is then refined by the existing LLRs on path representation and usage, so that the architecture can derive a distinct planning component and its interfaces more cleanly.
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--9">
    <ItemID>HL-RUN-1.2</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      HL-RUN-1.2: “The system shall perform a second run to the goal region after exploration” is refined by LL-RUN-1.2.1 and LL-RUN-1.2.2 which describe path retrieval and triggering. However, the HLR does not specify:
      - Whether the second run must start exactly at the start cell or may start elsewhere,
      - Whether the second run must use the same “fastest path” as defined in HL-RUN-1.3 (tight coupling) or could differ,
      - How failures during the second run are handled.
      This lack of precision at HLR-level introduces ambiguity in architectural responsibilities (e.g., control logic for second-run state vs fault handling), meaning not all aspects necessary for architecture design are clearly determined at the high level.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      - Clarify HL-RUN-1.2, for example:
        “The system shall, after successful return to the start cell, perform a second run from the start cell to the goal region using the fastest path defined in HL-RUN-1.3.”
      - Optionally add an additional HLR that defines failure handling for the second run (e.g., what to do on obstruction or timeout) and then add corresponding LLRs.
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--10">
    <ItemID>LL-INTERF-1.2.1</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      LL-INTERF-1.2.1 (“Actuator Command Abstraction”) refines HL-INTERF-1.2 and HL-HARDWARE-2.1 but there is no explicit LLR defining how this abstraction coordinates with:
      - Safety overrides from collision avoidance (LL-MAP-1.2.4),
      - Rate limiting (LL-INTERF-1.2.2),
      - High-speed mode for second run (LL-RUN-1.3.2).
      The abstract motion command layer is central to the overall architecture; lacking explicit refinement of command arbitration and priority (e.g., safety vs requested speed) means the current LLR set is insufficient to derive a complete and conflict-free motor control architecture.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      - Add one or more LLRs under the INTERF/HARDWARE/RUN groups specifying:
        - How the actuator abstraction layer arbitrates between normal motion commands, high-speed second-run commands, and safety overrides,
        - That collision avoidance commands always have highest priority and can override or clamp commanded speeds,
        - How rate limiting interacts with abrupt overrides.
      Example LLR:
      “The system shall implement a motion command arbiter that receives high-level motion commands, applies translational speed limits, and allows collision avoidance to override or reduce commands before issuing motor_set calls.”
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>Low Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>

  <Finding ID="LLR--1--11">
    <ItemID>LL-MAP-1.2.3</ItemID>
    <Severity>Catastrophic</Severity>
    <Description>
      LL-MAP-1.2.3 (“Wall Proximity Estimation”) assumes usage of ultrasonic and IR sensor models with specified ranges and orientation, but the corresponding HLRs (HL-INTERF-2.3, HL-INTERF-3.3, HL-INTERF-3.4) currently contain ambiguous characters (“�”) and vague “approximately” phrasing. For precise architecture design of the sensing and fusion module, the LLR depends on clear underlying sensor models. The current ambiguity at HLR level may lead to inconsistent implementations and violates SRP 2.1.1 (3) regarding non-contradiction and clarity.
    </Description>
    <Solution>
      - First correct and clarify the HLR text for ultrasonic accuracy and IR orientation/range (as described in earlier findings).
      - Then adjust LL-MAP-1.2.3 if necessary to reference the clarified ranges and tolerances (e.g., “IR detection range approximately 4 cm ± 1 cm at 25° orientation”), keeping LLR testable and consistent with the clarified HLRs.
    </Solution>
    <RollbackPhase>High Level Design</RollbackPhase>
  </Finding>
</Findings> 

